[[Image:Machurochelys liaoxiensis and Psittacosaurus.jpg|thumb|''Ordosemys liaoxiensis'' and ''Psittacosaurus'' preserved together]] {{Paleontology}} The [[Yixian Formation]] ({{zh|s=义县组|t=義縣組|p=Yìxiàn zǔ}}) is a [[geological formation]] in [[Jinzhou]], [[Liaoning]], [[People's Republic of China]], that spans about 5 million years during the [[early Cretaceous]] period (early [[Aptian]] stage). It is known for its [[fossil]]s, listed below.
The Yixian Formation is divided into the following subunits: (ages from Chang et al., 2009<ref name="age2009yixian">{{cite journal | last1 = Chang | first1 = S. C. | last2 = Zhang | first2 = H. | last3 = Renne | first3 = P. R. | last4 = Fang | first4 = Y. | year = 2009 | title = High-precision 40Ar/39Ar age for the Jehol Biota | url = | journal = Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology | volume = 280 | issue = 1| pages = 94–104 | doi=10.1016/j.palaeo.2009.06.021}}</ref> unless otherwise noted) * Jingangshan Bed (youngest, 122.1 Ma) * Dawangzhangzi Bed (124.4 Ma)<ref name="meng2008">{{cite journal | last1 = Meng | first1 = F.X. | last2 = Gao | first2 = S. | last3 = Liu | first3 = X.M. | title = U-Pb zircon geochronology and geochemistry of volcanic rocks of the Yixian Formation in the Lingyuan area, western Liaoning, China | journal = Geological Bulletin of China | volume = 27 | pages = 364–373 | date = 2008}}</ref> * Jianshangou Bed (125.2 Ma)<ref name="chang2017"/> * Lujiatun Bed (125.8 Ma)<ref name="chang2017">{{cite journal | last1 = Chang | first1 = S.-C. | last2 = Gao | first2 = K.-Q. | last3 = Zhou | first3 = Z.-F. | last4 = Jourdan | first4 = F. | date = 2017 | title = New chronostratigraphic constraints on the Yixian Formation with implications for the Jehol Biota | journal = Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology | doi = 10.1016/j.palaeo.2017.09.026 | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018217304832 | volume = 487 | pages = 399–406}}</ref> * Basalt base (oldest, 129.7 Ma)
