{{Infobox cricketer | name = Richard Evans | image = | country = South Africa | fullname = Richard James Evans | nickname = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1914|10|11|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[East London, Eastern Cape|East London]], South Africa | death_date = {{Death date and age|1943|5|29|1914|10|11|df=yes}} | death_place = At sea, off [[Cape Town]], South Africa | family = | heightft = | heightinch = | batting = Right-handed | bowling = Right-arm leg-spin | club1 = [[Border cricket team|Border]] | year1 = 1934-35 to 1939-40 | columns = 1 | column1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]] | matches1 = 10 | runs1 = 234 | bat avg1 = 13.00 | 100s/50s1 = 0/1 | top score1 = 88 | deliveries1 = 1543 | wickets1 = 49 | bowl avg1 = 18.48 | fivefor1 = 4 | tenfor1 = 2 | best bowling1 = 8/64 | catches/stumpings1 = 7/– | date = 20 January 2018 | source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/southafrica/content/player/44991.html Cricinfo }} '''Richard James Evans''' (11 October 1914 – 29 May 1943) was a [[South Africa]]n [[cricketer]] who played [[first-class cricket]] for [[Border cricket team|Border]] from 1934 to 1940.
Richard Evans was a leg-spin and googly bowler who had a very high career strike-rate: a wicket every 31.48 deliveries.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/13/13392/13392.html| title = Richard Evans| publisher = CricketArchive| subscription = yes | accessdate =16 February 2018}}</ref> He had an outstanding season in 1937-38 when he was 23. In the first match, against [[Western Province cricket team|Western Province]], he took 5 for 72 and 4 for 92, and Border won by seven wickets.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/16/16469.html | title = Western Province v Border 1937-38| publisher = CricketArchive| subscription = yes | accessdate =16 February 2018}}</ref> Then, in Border’s innings victory over [[Eastern Province cricket team|Eastern Province]] he took 4 for 50 and 6 for 40.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/16/16476.html | title = Eastern Province v Border 1937-38| publisher = CricketArchive| subscription = yes | accessdate =16 February 2018}}</ref> Later, in the victory over [[Free State cricket team|Orange Free State]], he took 5 for 27 and 2 for 28,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/16/16513.html| title = Border v Orange Free State 1937-38| publisher = CricketArchive| subscription = yes | accessdate =16 February 2018}}</ref> and a week after that, in the loss to [[Gauteng cricket team|Transvaal]], he took 2 for 29 and 8 for 64.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/16/16515.html| title = Border v Transvaal 1937-38| publisher = CricketArchive| subscription = yes | accessdate =16 February 2018}}</ref> He finished the season with 36 wickets in five matches off 867 balls at a bowling average of 13.11 and a strike-rate of a wicket every 24.08 balls. Only [[Norman Gordon]] of Transvaal, with 39 wickets off 1798 balls, took more wickets in the season.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/2/Currie_Cup_1937-38/Bowling_by_Average.html | title = Bowling by average, Currie Cup 1937-38| publisher = CricketArchive| subscription = yes | accessdate =16 February 2018}}</ref>
However, Evans's considerable promise was unfulfilled.<ref>[[Louis Duffus]], "The Past South African Season", ''[[The Cricketer]]'', 30 April 1938, p. 21.</ref> He played only two more first-class matches before the [[Second World War]], in which he died at sea off [[Cape Town]], aged 28.
