[[Brigadier (United Kingdom)|Brigadier]] '''Sir Henry Robert Kincaid Floyd, 5th Baronet'''<ref name="thepeerage">[http://www.thepeerage.com/p12699.htm#i126989 thePeerage.com]</ref> (7 May 1899 – 5 November 1968<ref name="thepeerage" />) was a British soldier.

Floyd was educated at [[Eton College]] and at the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]. He was an officer in the [[15th/19th Hussars]] and, having been promoted to [[Brigadier (United Kingdom)|brigadier]], during the [[World War II|Second World War]] he served as Brigadier General Staff (BGS) to [[VIII Corps (United Kingdom)|VIII Corps]], commanded by [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]] [[Richard O'Connor|Sir Richard O'Connor]]. He served with VIII Corps throughout [[Operation Overlord]] and was described as "a tower of strength to the new commander [O'Connor] and became a good friend as well".<ref>Baynes, p. 185</ref> From October 1944 he was [[chief of staff]] of the [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]], commanded by Lieutenant General [[Richard McCreery|Sir Richard McCreery]], from 1944 to 1945. Between 1961 and 1968 he served as [[Lord-Lieutenant of Buckinghamshire]].<ref name="bcc">[http://www.buckscc.gov.uk/bcc/content/index.jsp?contentid=660681331 20th century Lords Lieutenant] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217090109/http://www.buckscc.gov.uk/bcc/content/index.jsp?contentid=660681331 |date=17 February 2012 }}</ref>  A fervent supporter of [[horseriding]] and [[fox hunting]], he was killed in a riding accident at the age of 69.<ref name="bcc" />

The [[Sir Henry Floyd Grammar School]] in [[Aylesbury]] is named after him, as is part of the postgraduate medical centre at Stoke Mandeville Hospital.<ref name="bcc" />

